Age of nest when found. date_found - initiation_date_corrected.

Julian date that the nest was last checked and it's fate determined. Julian day 1 = 1 January. Corresponds to hatch date for successful nests.

'median' = median date between last day checked and day found empty, 'censor' = fate unknown or human caused, so nest is censored, 'day found' = day found nest empty, 'day prior' = day prior to finding nest empty, 'estimated hatch date' = used estimated hatch date for date hatched.  Other descriptions may have been used when necessary.

How corrected initiation and incubation dates were determined.

Identification of nest ID of previous nest user. 'unknown' = previous nest number unknown.
Whether old nest number is reliable.

CCMP = Culture Collection of Marine Phytoplankton. It is a unique culture collection clone identifier for NCMA (National Center for Marine Algae and Microbiota)

Treatment performed on culture collections. Only nitrogen (N:P) and irradiance (Light) were manipulated in these treatments, all other factors were similar to the control. For N:P and Light treatments, cultures were acclimated to the growth conditions for >10 generations.
Classification of growth phases
Letters A, B, C correspond to replicated culture collections; Each letter represents a replication that has had a certain combination of growth phase calculation and treatment done on it

Growth curves for each strain were generated by following changes in relative fluorescence units (RFU) from initial dilution through stationary growth, and growth rates calculated from the linear portion of the natural log transformed RFU data plotted against time.

Day of year in Coordinated Universal Time (UTC). Examples: 12:00, January 1, 2011  = day 1.00; 06:00, 06:00, May 20, 2011 = 140.25.

The x-coordinate position of a GPS station relative to the base station QING in the ITRF2005 spatial reference system (Information on the International Terrestrial Reference Frame can be found here: http://itrf.ensg.ign.fr/general.php and https://doi.org/10.1029/2007JB004949). The GPS basestation, QING, has ITRF2005 coordinates of x = 1433770.952 m	y = -1711771.97 m	z = 5955217.06 m. The x-coordinate is calculated as the mean of positions collected every 15 seconds for 15 minutes. Only coordinates with at least 95% of all possible position measurements within a 15 minute window are reported; each position is composed of between 57-60 individual position measurements.

The y-coordinate position of a GPS station relative to the base station QING in the ITRF2005 spatial reference system (Information on the International Terrestrial Reference Frame can be found here: http://itrf.ensg.ign.fr/general.php and https://doi.org/10.1029/2007JB004949). The GPS basestation, QING, has ITRF2005 coordinates of x = 1433770.952 m	y = -1711771.97 m	z = 5955217.06 m. The y-coordinate is calculated as the mean of positions collected every 15 seconds for 15 minutes. Only coordinates with at least 95% of all possible position measurements within a 15 minute window are reported; each position is composed of between 57-60 individual position measurements.

The z-coordinate position (elevation) of a GPS station relative to the base station QING in the ITRF2005 spatial reference system (Information on the International Terrestrial Reference Frame can be found here: http://itrf.ensg.ign.fr/general.php and https://doi.org/10.1029/2007JB004949). The GPS basestation, QING, has ITRF2005 coordinates of x = 1433770.952 m	y = -1711771.97 m	z = 5955217.06 m. The z-coordinate is calculated as the mean of positions collected every 15 seconds for 15 minutes. Only coordinates with at least 95% of all possible position measurements within a 15 minute window are reported; each position is composed of between 57-60 individual position measurements.

The uncertainty in meters of the x-coordinate position of a GPS station in the ITRF2005 reference frame. The uncertainty is calculated as 1-standard deviation of positions collected every 15 seconds for 15 minutes. Only uncertainties of coordinates with at least 95% of all possible position measurements within a 15 minute window are reported; each position is composed of between 57-60 individual position measurements.

The uncertainty in meters of the y-coordinate position of a GPS station in the ITRF2005 reference frame. The uncertainty is calculated as 1-standard deviation of positions collected every 15 seconds for 15 minutes. Only uncertainties of coordinates with at least 95% of all possible position measurements within a 15 minute window are reported; each position is composed of between 57-60 individual position measurements.

The uncertainty in meters of the z-coordinate position of a GPS station in the ITRF2005 reference frame. The uncertainty is calculated as 1-standard deviation of positions collected every 15 seconds for 15 minutes. Site (Main: Mesic, Hydric, or Xeric).

Treatment (Main: Ancillary, Snowfence, Control, fertilized.) The main treatment of this experiment are snowfences built around trees at an arctic treeline (to induce larger snowdrifts). Similar trees were also selected for the control plots which have no fence. To reduce the impact of soil sampling on these trees over the course of four years an additional set of controls named the Ancillary plots were set up. The fertilized treatment NPK fertilizer containing 10 g/m2 nitrogen (N), 5 g/m2 phosphorus (P) and 10 g/m2 potassium (K) was evenly applied 1.5 m away from the main stem of each tree. N from: (NH4)2SO4, P from: P2O5, and K from: KCl. Fertilizer was applied early June of 2015 and 2016 (Methods and more information about these trees see: Ellison, S.B., et al., Poor nutrition as a potential cause of divergent tree growth near the Arctic treeline in northern Alaska. Ecology, 2019. 100(12): p. e02878.).

the frost in the reference (zenith = 90 degree elevation) spectrum

the number of the measurement in the sequence. This number sequentially increases within the same rectimedate

uncalibrated intensity of the measurement at 310nm. This is in dark and offset corrected counts per second (cps) at the detector; 0 cps implies no light. Note that the wavelength scale is a nominal scale and may differ slightly from true wavelength. Normally 310nm is used, but not all instruments had this wavelength within their spectral range, so if 310nm was out of range, the shortest reasonable wavelength was chosen and the name will differ.
intensity at 340nm, which all instruments should have within their spectral range.
intensity at 360.8nm, the peak of an O4 absorption band. All instruments have this wavelength
intensity at 397nm. Some instruments do not have 397nm, so the longest feasible wavelength is used if 397nm is out of range.

This field contains the number of years that the lake was considered to have a floating ice regime.
This field contains the number of years analyzed for each lake.
This field is the quotient of count_FI and count_year.  When multiplied by 100, it is the percent of years that the lake was considered to have a floating ice regime.

Four categories are possible: BI; lake is classified as having a bedfast ice regime for 90% or more of the years analyzed. FI;lake is classified as having a floating ice regime for 90% or more of the years analyzed. INT;lake is classified as FI less than 90% of the years analyzed and BI less than 90% of the years analyzed yet shows no statistically significant trend from one regime to the other merely oscillating between floating and bedfast. TRANS-FI; lake is considered to be transitioning from bedfast to floating ice during the analysis time frame.  Specifically the lake must be classified as FI less than 90% of the years analyzed and BI less than 90% of the years analyzed. In addition to these two conditions the lake must also show a statistically significant trend (p < 0.05 least squares regression) from bedfast to floating ice. TRANS-BI; lake is considered to be transitioning from floating to bedfast ice during the analysis time frame.  Specifically the lake must be classified as FI less than 90% of the years analyzed and BI less than 90% of the years analyzed. In addition to these two conditions, the lake must also show a statistically significant trend (p < 0.05 least squares regression) from floating to bedfast ice.
Contains quality control notes and lake depths from a depth database compiled from published data.

This field is the quotient of count_FI and count_year.  When multiplied by 100, it is the percent of years that the lake was considered to have a floating ice regime.

Four categories are possible: BI; lake is classified as having a bedfast ice regime for 90% or more of the years analyzed. FI;lake is classified as having a floating ice regime for 90% or more of the years analyzed. INT;lake is classified as FI less than 90% of the years analyzed and BI less than 90% of the years analyzed yet shows no statistically significant trend from one regime to the other merely oscillating between floating and bedfast. TRANS-FI; lake is considered to be transitioning from bedfast to floating ice during the analysis time frame.  Specifically the lake must be classified as FI less than 90% of the years analyzed and BI less than 90% of the years analyzed. In addition to these two conditions the lake must also show a statistically significant trend (p < 0.05 least squares regression) from bedfast to floating ice. TRANS-BI; lake is considered to be transitioning from floating to bedfast ice during the analysis time frame.  Specifically the lake must be classified as FI less than 90% of the years analyzed and BI less than 90% of the years analyzed. In addition to these two conditions, the lake must also show a statistically significant trend (p < 0.05 least squares regression) from floating to bedfast ice.

This field contains the number of years that the lake was considered to have a floating ice regime.
This field contains the number of years analyzed for each lake.
This field is the quotient of count_FI and count_year.  When multiplied by 100, it is the percent of years that the lake was considered to have a floating ice regime.

Four categories are possible: BI; lake is classified as having a bedfast ice regime for 90% or more of the years analyzed. FI;lake is classified as having a floating ice regime for 90% or more of the years analyzed. INT;lake is classified as FI less than 90% of the years analyzed and BI less than 90% of the years analyzed yet shows no statistically significant trend from one regime to the other merely oscillating between floating and bedfast. TRANS-FI; lake is considered to be transitioning from bedfast to floating ice during the analysis time frame.  Specifically the lake must be classified as FI less than 90% of the years analyzed and BI less than 90% of the years analyzed. In addition to these two conditions the lake must also show a statistically significant trend (p < 0.05 least squares regression) from bedfast to floating ice. TRANS-BI; lake is considered to be transitioning from floating to bedfast ice during the analysis time frame.  Specifically the lake must be classified as FI less than 90% of the years analyzed and BI less than 90% of the years analyzed. In addition to these two conditions, the lake must also show a statistically significant trend (p < 0.05 least squares regression) from floating to bedfast ice.
Contains quality control notes and lake depths from a depth database compiled from published data.

This field is copied from the Western Arctic Coastal Plain (Jones, B.M., & Grosse, G. (2013). Western Arctic Coastal Plain, Lakes and Drainage Gradients. In A.L.C. Cooperative (Ed.): Arctic Landscape Conservation Cooperative. http://arcticlcc.org/products/spatial-data/show/western-arctic-coastal-plain-lakes-and-drainage-gradients) lake shapefile dataset and is the area of a lake polygon derived from the IfSAR data in square kilometers.

This field is copied from the Western Arctic Coastal Plain (Jones, B.M., & Grosse, G. (2013). Western Arctic Coastal Plain, Lakes and Drainage Gradients. In A.L.C. Cooperative (Ed.): Arctic Landscape Conservation Cooperative. http://arcticlcc.org/products/spatial-data/show/western-arctic-coastal-plain-lakes-and-drainage-gradients) lake shapefile dataset and is the minimum digital surface model elevation value for a given polygon. This field is not present in the Umiat and Kuparuk regions.

This field is the lake ID from the Western Arctic Coastal Plain (Jones, B.M., & Grosse, G. (2013). Western Arctic Coastal Plain, Lakes and Drainage Gradients. In A.L.C. Cooperative (Ed.): Arctic Landscape Conservation Cooperative. http://arcticlcc.org/products/spatial-data/show/western-arctic-coastal-plain-lakes-and-drainage-gradients) dataset if the region was covered by that dataset. Otherwise the region ID is a unique lake ID for that region.

This field is the quotient of count_FI and count_year.  When multiplied by 100, it is the percent of years that the lake was considered to have a floating ice regime.

Four categories are possible: BI; lake is classified as having a bedfast ice regime for 90% or more of the years analyzed. FI;lake is classified as having a floating ice regime for 90% or more of the years analyzed. INT;lake is classified as FI less than 90% of the years analyzed and BI less than 90% of the years analyzed yet shows no statistically significant trend from one regime to the other merely oscillating between floating and bedfast. TRANS-FI; lake is considered to be transitioning from bedfast to floating ice during the analysis time frame.  Specifically the lake must be classified as FI less than 90% of the years analyzed and BI less than 90% of the years analyzed. In addition to these two conditions the lake must also show a statistically significant trend (p < 0.05 least squares regression) from bedfast to floating ice. TRANS-BI; lake is considered to be transitioning from floating to bedfast ice during the analysis time frame.  Specifically the lake must be classified as FI less than 90% of the years analyzed and BI less than 90% of the years analyzed. In addition to these two conditions, the lake must also show a statistically significant trend (p < 0.05 least squares regression) from floating to bedfast ice.

This field contains the number of years that the lake was considered to have a floating ice regime.
This field contains the number of years analyzed for each lake.
This field is the quotient of count_FI and count_year.  When multiplied by 100, it is the percent of years that the lake was considered to have a floating ice regime.

Four categories are possible: BI; lake is classified as having a bedfast ice regime for 90% or more of the years analyzed. FI;lake is classified as having a floating ice regime for 90% or more of the years analyzed. INT;lake is classified as FI less than 90% of the years analyzed and BI less than 90% of the years analyzed yet shows no statistically significant trend from one regime to the other merely oscillating between floating and bedfast. TRANS-FI; lake is considered to be transitioning from bedfast to floating ice during the analysis time frame.  Specifically the lake must be classified as FI less than 90% of the years analyzed and BI less than 90% of the years analyzed. In addition to these two conditions the lake must also show a statistically significant trend (p < 0.05 least squares regression) from bedfast to floating ice. TRANS-BI; lake is considered to be transitioning from floating to bedfast ice during the analysis time frame.  Specifically the lake must be classified as FI less than 90% of the years analyzed and BI less than 90% of the years analyzed. In addition to these two conditions, the lake must also show a statistically significant trend (p < 0.05 least squares regression) from floating to bedfast ice.

Latitude in degrees North or South of the equator, with North being a positive value and South being negative.

Up to four descriptive navigation terms from the logbook entry, separated by a semi-colon ( ; ). For example, "working; along; slow".
